61
00:03:26,110 --> 00:03:28,830
Mistake number one, "I went there by bus."

62
00:03:28,830 --> 00:03:30,170
"I went there by car."

63
00:03:30,170 --> 00:03:32,180
"I went there by plane."

64
00:03:32,180 --> 00:03:37,129
Okay, so grammatically in a textbook, they
would say this is okay.

65
00:03:37,129 --> 00:03:38,129
But do you know what?

66
00:03:38,129 --> 00:03:43,960
In daily conversation, we rarely use "by"
plus transportation.

67
00:03:43,960 --> 00:03:47,490
I went there by car, by bus, by plane, by
taxi.

68
00:03:47,490 --> 00:03:51,750
It feels a little bit like textbook English
or classroom English.

69
00:03:51,750 --> 00:03:55,160
Instead, we're more likely to use the verb
"take".

70
00:03:55,160 --> 00:03:57,570
"I took a bus."

71
00:03:57,570 --> 00:03:59,269
"I took a train."

72
00:03:59,269 --> 00:04:00,569
"I took a flight."

73
00:04:00,569 --> 00:04:02,330
"I took the plane."

74
00:04:02,330 --> 00:04:08,560
With driving, because you're the one who is
in control, we often just say drive.

75
00:04:08,560 --> 00:04:11,180
I drove to my friend's house.

76
00:04:11,180 --> 00:04:13,190
We drove to the beach.

77
00:04:13,190 --> 00:04:16,920
That's in the past tense, to drive, drove.

78
00:04:16,920 --> 00:04:21,829
But here, we're more likely to use a verb
instead of a by phrase.

79
00:04:21,829 --> 00:04:23,559
So take a look at this sentence.

80
00:04:23,559 --> 00:04:27,460
How can we change it to make it be a little
bit more natural?

81
00:04:27,460 --> 00:04:31,110
"We're going to Canada by plane next week."

82
00:04:31,110 --> 00:04:32,759
You see that phrase "by plane".

83
00:04:32,759 --> 00:04:37,370
And now you know it's not so natural, how
can we change this up?

84
00:04:37,370 --> 00:04:39,960
Well, we have two options.

85
00:04:39,960 --> 00:04:41,169
We can use the verb "take".

86
00:04:41,169 --> 00:04:44,999
"We are taking a flight to Canada."

87
00:04:44,999 --> 00:04:47,960
Or you could just say, "We're flying to Canada."

88
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:52,349
It doesn't mean you're a bird and you are
actually flying.

89
00:04:52,349 --> 00:04:55,759
This implies that you are going into the airplane.

90
00:04:55,759 --> 00:04:58,810
So you could say, "We're taking a flight,"
or, "We're flying."

91
00:04:58,810 --> 00:05:04,689
Both of these are great options and you can
see how we use the verb to describe the action

92
00:05:04,689 --> 00:05:06,289
instead of a "by" phrase.

93
00:05:06,289 --> 00:05:11,120
Yes, you will occasionally hear this, but
I want to empower you to use the most natural

94
00:05:11,120 --> 00:05:12,120
phrase possible.

95
00:05:12,120 --> 00:05:17,720
All right, let's go to our second grammar
mistake that is commonly made by English learners.

96
00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:20,650
"I have 33 years."

97
00:05:20,650 --> 00:05:21,780
Huh?

98
00:05:21,780 --> 00:05:22,909
No.

99
00:05:22,909 --> 00:05:27,490
When we're talking about age, we do not use
"have".

100
00:05:27,490 --> 00:05:33,689
instead we can say, "I am 33 years old."

101
00:05:33,689 --> 00:05:34,689
"I am."

102
00:05:34,689 --> 00:05:37,620
We use a "be" verb to talk about age.

103
00:05:37,620 --> 00:05:42,960
This is something that I commonly see in my
students who speak a romantic language like

104
00:05:42,960 --> 00:05:46,369
Brazilian-Portuguese or Spanish or Italian
or French.

105
00:05:46,369 --> 00:05:49,659
I often hear, "I have 60 years."

106
00:05:49,659 --> 00:05:52,369
"I have 55 years."

107
00:05:52,369 --> 00:05:55,259
But instead we can have a little switch and
just say "am".

108
00:05:55,259 --> 00:05:58,319
"I am 66 years old."

109
00:05:58,319 --> 00:06:00,999
"I am 40 years old."

110
00:06:00,999 --> 00:06:01,999
Beautiful.

111
00:06:01,999 --> 00:06:07,210
Common grammar mistake number three is, "We
were five people at the party."

112
00:06:07,210 --> 00:06:09,060
Huh?

113
00:06:09,060 --> 00:06:12,789
This sounds very clunky and confusing in English.

114
00:06:12,789 --> 00:06:17,129
It's like there were five people in your head.

115
00:06:17,129 --> 00:06:18,129
What?

116
00:06:18,129 --> 00:06:19,960
We were five people.

117
00:06:19,960 --> 00:06:21,909
It's very confusing in English.

118
00:06:21,909 --> 00:06:28,499
So instead, it's much more natural, and in
fact, just better grammar to say, "There were

119
00:06:28,499 --> 00:06:31,249
five people at the party."

120
00:06:31,249 --> 00:06:35,539
Or you could say, "There were five of us at
the party."

121
00:06:35,539 --> 00:06:40,190
If you want to include yourself, the word
"us" includes yourself.

122
00:06:40,190 --> 00:06:45,999
So you could say, "There were five of us at
the party," or, "There were five people at

123
00:06:45,999 --> 00:06:46,999
the party."

124
00:06:46,999 --> 00:06:52,020
Both of those are excellent and they use the
word "there" instead of "we".

125
00:06:52,020 --> 00:06:53,839
"We were five people."

126
00:06:53,839 --> 00:06:54,839
No.

127
00:06:54,839 --> 00:06:56,469
"There were five people."

128
00:06:56,469 --> 00:06:57,469
Great.

129
00:06:57,469 --> 00:07:01,229
Grammar mistake number four is, "Don't be
scary."

130
00:07:01,229 --> 00:07:02,229
Huh?

131
00:07:02,229 --> 00:07:03,349
Is it Halloween?

132
00:07:03,349 --> 00:07:05,629
Are you dressed up like a vampire?

133
00:07:05,629 --> 00:07:08,240
Don't be scary there's children here.

134
00:07:08,240 --> 00:07:12,849
No, this phrase means stop scaring people.

135
00:07:12,849 --> 00:07:16,360
You're dressed up as something really scary.

136
00:07:16,360 --> 00:07:17,789
Stop being scary.

137
00:07:17,789 --> 00:07:18,819
Don't be scary.

138
00:07:18,819 --> 00:07:24,830
No, instead, a much more common phrase is,
"Don't be scared."

139
00:07:24,830 --> 00:07:30,349
I find that when my English students want
to say, "Don't be scared," they accidentally

140
00:07:30,349 --> 00:07:32,960
say, "Don't be scary," which has a very different
meaning.

141
00:07:32,960 --> 00:07:36,069
You are dressed up as something scary for
Halloween.

142
00:07:36,069 --> 00:07:42,240
So when you're trying to comfort someone or
soothe someone, you could say, "Don't be scared.

143
00:07:42,240 --> 00:07:47,240
I know that speaking English can be a little
bit difficult and maybe you feel nervous,

144
00:07:47,240 --> 00:07:48,720
but don't be scared.

145
00:07:48,720 --> 00:07:49,720
I'm nice.

146
00:07:49,720 --> 00:07:52,810
I hope that you can speak with me and feel
comfortable.

147
00:07:52,810 --> 00:07:53,849
Don't be scared."

148
00:07:53,849 --> 00:07:58,599
